{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e1795e6f-39b1-4e1f-a80d-a398f9c017a9","content":"No repo-specific docs on this topic, so here's the general guidance:\n\nOn macOS, when `createdump` isn't available (common with NativeAOT), you can capture crash dumps via the OS:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **If `/cores/` is empty**, macOS may have core dumps disabled at the kernel level:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n4. **Run your app** — when it crashes, look for `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **If core dumps aren't generated**, check:\n   - Disk space (cores can be large)\n   - SIP restrictions (`csrutil status`)\n   - The app's entitlements (sandboxed apps may not write cores)\n\n7. **Alternative — use macOS Crash Reporter logs** at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` files contain stack traces and register state automatically.\n\nFor .NET NativeAOT specifically, the crash reporter logs are often the quickest path since they require no setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"50a980a7-375f-4138-8a68-dea140519d44","outputTokens":352},"id":"14f64529-12fc-4776-b3c7-82336f075993","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:58:36.588Z","parentId":"020b9453-0bff-4b29-9e7e-6a3aa8a67813"}
